SIMPLE: guest
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Guest
<hw>Guest</hw> <pr>(g⟦ecr⟧st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>gest</ets>, AS. <ets>g⟦ae⟧st</ets>, <ets>gest</ets>; akin to OS.,
D., & G. <ets>gast</ets>, Icel. <ets>gestr</ets>, Sw.
<ets>g⟦aum⟧st</ets>, Dan. <ets>Gj⟦aum⟧st</ets>, Goth. <ets>gasts</ets>,
Russ. <ets>goste</ets>, and to L. <ets>hostis</ets> enemy, stranger; the
meaning <ets>stranger</ets> is the older one, but the root is unknown.
Cf. <er>Host</er> an army, <er>Hostile</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
visitor; a person received and entertained in one's house or at one's
table; a visitor entertained without pay.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To cheer his <qex>guests</qex>, whom he had stayed that night.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>True friendship's laws are by this rule exprest.⟦br⟧
Welcome the coming, speed the parting <qex>guest</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A lodger or a boarder at a hotel, lodging house, or
boarding house.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Any insect that
lives in the nest of another without compulsion and usually not as a
parasite.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>An inquiline.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Guest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Guest
<hw>Guest</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To receive or
entertain hospitably.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Sylvester.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Guest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Guest
<hw>Guest</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be, or act the part of, a
guest.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And tell me, best of princes, who he was⟦br⟧
That <qex>guested</qex> here so late.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Guest rope</ent>⟦br⟧
